8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 209, L.D. 470, “An Act to Require
10 School Administrative Units to Adopt Mentoring Programs for Teachers and to Improve
11 Existing Programs”
12 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
13 'Resolve, Directing the Department of Education to Review Teacher Mentoring
14 Programs in Maine Public Schools'
15 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
16 'Sec. 1. Teacher mentoring programs; review. Resolved: That the
17 Department of Education, in collaboration with the Maine Education Association, the
18 Maine School Management Association and Educate Maine, shall conduct a review of
19 teacher mentoring programs in public schools in the State. The review must include, but
20 is not limited to:
21 1. The number of teachers holding emergency teacher certificates, conditional teacher
22 certificates and new teacher certificates with less than 3 years of experience employed at
23 each school administrative unit;
24 2. Verification that every teacher holding an emergency teacher certificate, a
25 conditional teacher certificate or a new teacher certificate with less than 3 years of
26 experience is assigned a mentor;
27 3. Interviews with public school principals about teacher mentoring programs; and
28 4. A compilation of descriptions of basic requirements of teacher mentoring programs
29 throughout the State, including the structure of each program, training and available
30 stipends.
31 Sec. 2. Report. Resolved: That, by February 15, 2026, the Department of
32 Education shall submit a report to the Joint Standing Committee on Education and Cultural
33 Affairs based on the review conducted pursuant to section 1. The joint standing committee
34 may report out legislation related to the report to the Second Regular Session of the 132nd
35 Legislature.
